@@eThe Templar Tradition@@N

@@yThe Temple-Guard Auxiliaries@@N
The Templar title descends from the Solar Court's temple-guard auxiliaries, wardens
who stood at the boundary between battle-clergy and ceremonial ministry. The five
offices of the Solar Court each had dedicated practitioners, but between those
offices and the physical infrastructure they maintained lay a threshold role that
none considered their primary responsibility. The auxiliaries managed that
threshold, and the job required both combat capacity and consecration skill. A
warden who could defend but not consecrate after a desecration was incomplete, and
one who could consecrate but not prevent desecration was equally so.

@@yThe Paladin-Priest Separation@@N
After the Sundering Wars, the Paladin vanguard and the Priest ward-keepers settled
into deliberately separate roles: one advancing, one sustaining. What began as
temporary specialization became permanent institutional identity over generations.
Paladin academies optimized for advance-and-sanctify; Priest communities optimized
for sustained restoration. Practitioners in each tradition found that crossing the
divide required something close to starting over, as each had lost fluency in the
other's domain.

@@yThe Garrison Crisis@@N
The synthesis was forced by necessity during the Violet Compact's founding years,
when combined Paladin-Priest forces assigned to garrison waystation sites found
themselves too few to maintain separate functions. Some began learning the other
tradition's techniques to cover gaps. Others developed integrated methods: striking
techniques incorporating consecration effects, healing techniques performed without
requiring stable positions. They found, unexpectedly, that integration at depth
produced qualitatively different results than minimum-coverage cross-training.

@@yStanding Between Two Callings@@N
The practitioners who achieved genuine depth in both functions revived the old Solar
Court title for what it meant: standing between two callings at once. The Violet
Compact absorbed the resulting Corps as a sanctioned order. Their most sophisticated
contribution is the integration of healing with status-cure functions within a
single working, eliminating the treatment gap of sequential application. The
Templar tradition holds that the Paladin's advance and the Priest's restoration are
not two functions requiring two specialists but one function requiring a
practitioner who can shift between them as conditions require.
